## **4. Memory Sanitizers - Runtime Detection**

### **4a. KASAN (Kernel Address Sanitizer)**

**What it does**: Detects out-of-bounds accesses and use-after-free bugs at runtime.

**Key Files**: `mm/kasan/`, `mm/kasan/generic.c`, `mm/kasan/report.c`

### **Code Sample - KASAN Instrumentation**:
```c
// From mm/kasan/generic.c
void __asan_load8(unsigned long addr)
{
    check_memory_region(addr, 8, false, _RET_IP_);
}

static void check_memory_region(unsigned long addr, size_t size,
                                bool write, unsigned long ret_ip)
{
    if (unlikely(size == 0))
        return;

    if (unlikely((void *)addr < kasan_shadow_to_mem(kasan_mem_to_shadow_start))) {
        kasan_report(addr, size, write, ret_ip);
    }
}
```

**How it works**: 
- Creates "shadow memory" (1 byte of shadow for every 8 bytes of memory)
- Compiler instruments every memory access to check shadow memory
- Detects: buffer overflows, use-after-free, stack out-of-bounds

### **Code Sample - KASAN Report**:
```c
// From mm/kasan/report.c
void kasan_report(unsigned long addr, size_t size, bool is_write, 
                  unsigned long ip)
{
    struct kasan_access_info info;

    info.access_addr = (void *)addr;
    info.access_size = size;
    info.is_write = is_write;
    info.ip = ip;

    print_error_description(&info);
    print_address_description(addr);
    print_memory_metadata((void *)addr);
    dump_stack();
}
```

### **4b. KFENCE (Kernel Electric Fence)**

**What it does**: Lightweight memory error detector using guard pages.

**Key Files**: `mm/kfence/core.c`

### **Code Sample - KFENCE Guard Pages**:
```c
// From mm/kfence/core.c
static void *kfence_guarded_alloc(struct kmem_cache *cache, size_t size,
                                   gfp_t gfp)
{
    struct kfence_metadata *meta;
    unsigned long flags;
    void *addr;

    // Allocate with guard pages on both sides
    meta = kfence_get_metadata();
    addr = kfence_alloc(meta, size, gfp);

    // Set up guard pages - page faults on out-of-bounds access
    kfence_protect(meta->addr);

    return addr + meta->offset;
}
```

**How it works**: Surrounds allocations with unmapped guard pages that trigger page faults on overflow.

---

## **5. Stack Protection**

### **5a. Stack Canaries**

**What it does**: Places random values on the stack before return addresses to detect buffer overflows.

**Key Files**: `kernel/fork.c`, `arch/x86/kernel/process.c`

### **Code Sample - Stack Canary Setup**:
```c
// From kernel/fork.c
static struct task_struct *dup_task_struct(struct task_struct *orig, int node)
{
    struct task_struct *tsk;
    unsigned long *stack;

    tsk = alloc_task_struct_node(node);
    if (!tsk)
        return NULL;

    stack = alloc_thread_stack_node(tsk, node);
    if (!stack)
        goto free_tsk;

    // Set up stack canary
    tsk->stack_canary = get_random_canary();

    return tsk;
}

// Compiler checks canary before function return
// If changed -> buffer overflow detected -> panic
```

### **5b. Stack Erasing (STACKLEAK)**

**What it does**: Erases kernel stack on return to userspace, preventing information leaks.

**Key Files**: `arch/x86/kernel/stackleak.c`

### **Code Sample - Stack Erasing**:
```c
// From kernel/stackleak.c (GCC plugin)
asmlinkage void stackleak_erase(void)
{
    unsigned long *sp, boundary, left_to_erase;

    sp = (unsigned long *)&sp;
    boundary = current->lowest_stack;

    // Erase everything from current SP to lowest used
    while (sp < boundary) {
        *sp = STACKLEAK_POISON;
        sp++;
    }

    current->lowest_stack = current_top_of_stack() - THREAD_SIZE/64;
}
```

**Purpose**: 
- Prevents kernel stack information leaks to userspace
- Reduces risk from uninitialized variable vulnerabilities

---

## **6. CPU Vulnerability Mitigations (Spectre/Meltdown)**

### **6a. Spectre v1 - Bounds Check Bypass**

**Mitigation**: Speculative execution barriers and array index masking.

**Key Files**: `arch/x86/kernel/cpu/bugs.c`

### **Code Sample - Spectre v1 Mitigation**:
```c
// From include/linux/nospec.h
#define array_index_nospec(index, size)                    \
({                                                          \
    typeof(index) _i = (index);                            \
    typeof(size) _s = (size);                              \
    unsigned long _mask = array_index_mask_nospec(_i, _s); \
    BUILD_BUG_ON(sizeof(_i) > sizeof(long));               \
    BUILD_BUG_ON(sizeof(_s) > sizeof(long));               \
    (typeof(_i)) (_i & _mask);                             \
})

// Masks the index to ensure speculative execution can't leak data
static inline unsigned long array_index_mask_nospec(unsigned long index,
                                                     unsigned long size)
{
    return ~(long)(index | (size - 1UL - index)) >> (BITS_PER_LONG - 1);
}
```

### **6b. Spectre v2 - Branch Target Injection**

**Mitigation**: Retpoline (return trampoline) and IBRS (Indirect Branch Restricted Speculation).

### **Code Sample - Retpoline**:
```c
// From arch/x86/kernel/cpu/bugs.c
void __init spectre_v2_select_mitigation(void)
{
    enum spectre_v2_mitigation_cmd cmd = spectre_v2_parse_cmdline();
    enum spectre_v2_mitigation mode = SPECTRE_V2_NONE;

    if (boot_cpu_has(X86_FEATURE_IBRS)) {
        mode = SPECTRE_V2_IBRS_ENHANCED;
    } else if (boot_cpu_has(X86_FEATURE_RETPOLINE)) {
        mode = SPECTRE_V2_RETPOLINE;
    }

    setup_force_cpu_cap(X86_FEATURE_RSB_CTXSW);
    spectre_v2_enabled = mode;
    pr_info("%s\n", spectre_v2_strings[mode]);
}

// Retpoline assembly pattern - prevents speculative indirect jumps
#define RETPOLINE_CALL                              \
    "call __x86_indirect_thunk_%V[thunk_target]\n"
```

### **6c. Meltdown - Addressed by PTI**

Already covered above in PTI section. PTI isolates kernel page tables to prevent Meltdown attacks.

### **6d. L1TF / Foreshadow - L1 Terminal Fault**

**Mitigation**: Flush L1 cache on context switches and VM entry.

### **Code Sample - L1 Cache Flushing**:
```c
// From arch/x86/kernel/cpu/bugs.c
static void l1tf_select_mitigation(void)
{
    if (!boot_cpu_has_bug(X86_BUG_L1TF))
        return;

    setup_force_cpu_cap(X86_FEATURE_FLUSH_L1D);
    pr_info("Mitigation: PTE Inversion; VMX: flush L1D on vmentry\n");
}

// Actual flushing code in arch/x86/kvm/vmx/vmx.c
static void vmx_l1d_flush(struct kvm_vcpu *vcpu)
{
    wrmsrl(MSR_IA32_FLUSH_CMD, L1D_FLUSH);
}
```

