## **7. Additional Memory Security Mechanisms**

### **7a. DEP (Data Execution Prevention) / NX Bit**

**What it does**: Marks memory pages as non-executable to prevent code injection attacks.

### **Code Sample - NX Bit Usage**:
```c
// From arch/x86/include/asm/pgtable_types.h
#define _PAGE_NX    (_AT(pteval_t, 1) << _PAGE_BIT_NX)

// Applied to data pages
#define PAGE_KERNEL    __pgprot(__PAGE_KERNEL | _PAGE_NX)

// Executable pages explicitly clear NX
#define PAGE_KERNEL_EXEC   __pgprot(__PAGE_KERNEL & ~_PAGE_NX)
```

Every data page (stack, heap, etc.) has NX bit set, preventing execution.

### **7b. Kernel Lockdown**

**What it does**: Restricts kernel functionality that could be used to compromise security.

**Key Files**: `security/lockdown/lockdown.c`

### **Code Sample - Lockdown Enforcement**:
```c
// From security/lockdown/lockdown.c
int security_locked_down(enum lockdown_reason what)
{
    if (kernel_locked_down >= what) {
        pr_notice("Lockdown: %s is restricted; see man kernel_lockdown.7\n",
                  lockdown_reasons[what]);
        return -EPERM;
    }
    return 0;
}

// Blocks: /dev/mem access, kexec, hibernation, etc.
```

### **7c. Seccomp (Secure Computing Mode)**

**What it does**: Restricts syscalls a process can make, limiting attack surface.

**Key Files**: `kernel/seccomp.c`

### **Code Sample - Seccomp Filter**:
```c
// From kernel/seccomp.c
static long seccomp_set_mode_filter(unsigned int flags,
                                     const char __user *filter)
{
    struct seccomp_filter *prepared;
    long ret;

    prepared = seccomp_prepare_filter(filter);
    if (IS_ERR(prepared))
        return PTR_ERR(prepared);

    current->seccomp.filter = prepared;
    current->seccomp.mode = SECCOMP_MODE_FILTER;

    return 0;
}
```

Used by sandboxes (Chrome, systemd, containers) to restrict process capabilities.

